The Telegraph - Calcutta : Business

 Business Briefs

 Mumbai, Feb. 8: Gold met with heavy selling pressure and plunged by a whopping Rs 270 per 10 grams on the bullion market here today due to a steep fall in the global prices following heavy profit-selling by funds. Silver also crashed by Rs 185 per kilo. Standard gold (99.5 purity) resumed trading on a sharply lower note at Rs 7,960 and fell further before ending at Rs 7,940, a loss of Rs 270 over the previous close of Rs 8,210. Similarly, pure gold (99.9 purity) also opened low at Rs 7,995 and ended at Rs 7,980 compared with yesterday?s close of Rs 8,250.

 Jalandhar, Feb. 8: The government will soon announce a new steel policy to regulate prices, which have been fluctuating due to domestic factors and the international price situation, said steel minister Ram Vilas Paswan.

 New Delhi, Feb. 8: Citigroup will pick up a 5 per cent stake in Smera, a rating agency for small firms and have a strategic tie up. Citicorp Finance (India) Ltd today signed an MoU with Smera to jointly finance the SME business in India.

 New Delhi, Feb. 8: The government today said foreign direct investment in IT and telecom sectors is expected to go up by more than 100 per cent in 2006.

 Mumbai, Feb. 8: The South Indian Bank Ltd has fixed the price band of its follow-on public offer at Rs 60-66 per share. The offer opens on February 10 and closes on February 15.

 Mumbai, Feb. 8: Indian Banks? Association is still to finalise the benchmark prime lending rate issue and said would submit its recommendations to the Reserve Bank this month.

 New Delhi, Feb. 8: The government?s plan to sell residual shares in Balco could get delayed, as it was not happy with the value pegged by the advisor for the stake. ?The valuation of the government?s 49 per cent stake in Balco is not up to its expectations. It might go for a revaluation of the stake,? sources said.




